<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="879" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d879">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12945, 12949.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Silliman</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico City</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 20, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>General Carranza made a triumphal entry into the capital this morning.
                            The Plaza de Armas was thronged with many thousands. He spoke from one
                            of the balconies of the National Palace. Tremendous ovation and no
                            disorder whatever. The only representative of the local Diplomatic Corps
                            present was the French Chargé d’Affaires. In his speech Carranza made
                            appreciative reference to the Administration’s Mexican policy.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>